The finest wines of the Bordeaux region are those of the Médoc Graves, Sauternes and Saint-Emilion districts. They are usually kept in the cask for three years and then bottled at the Chateau Or in Bordeaux.

White wines of the first growth Graves are extremely delicate have a light bouquet and much vigor. They are comparatively dry. with the exception of those which come from the Cérons ane Podensac districts.

Sauternes are sweet, ranging from simple district growths to the inimitable Chateau d’Yquem, the finest of all naturally sweet wines and in a class by itself.

In 1855, the greatest growths of clarets were classified as io quality by an official committee and this classificdtion still holds good. Most of the wines in this list are mis en bouteilles au chateau, or chateau. bottled, which simply means that the wine was bottled where it was made and by the people who made it. It is a certain guarantee of authenticity but not necessarily of quality.
